ks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor Chetwode was born in 1507, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Chetwode, was 34 and her mother, Cicely Ellen Beresford, was 46. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with William de Clayton. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1507–Deceased":"1507–Surnud","1500–1536":"1500–1536","1505–1535":"1505–1535","1506–Male":"1506–Surnud","1507–Female":"1507–Surnud","1521–Female":"1521–Surnud","1525–Male":"1525–Surnud","1500–1582":"1500–1582","1524–1589":"1524–1589","1535–1588":"1535–1588","1632–1637":"1632–1637","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1461–1520":"1461–1520","1473":"1473","1461":"1461","1582":"1582","1525":"1525","1